full_caption: An interior architectural photo of Coffered Ceiling. Interior view of a domed ceiling with an oculus. Photographer description: Pantheon Oculus - Sacred Light Through Ancient Rome’s Open Dome. Mesmerizing view of the Pantheon’s famous oculus, the circular opening at the apex of the coffered dome that serves as the only source of natural light. This architectural marvel showcases brilliant sunlight streaming through the 9-meter opening, illuminating the intricate geometric patterns of the coffered ceiling. The oculus has remained unchanged for nearly 2,000 years, creating a divine connection between earth and sky that transforms throughout the day as light moves across the ancient stone..

full_caption: An interior architectural photo of Archway. Arched hallway in a dark, ancient stone building.. Photographer description: The interior corridor of Masjid Moth is built entirely of stone and lined with repeating arches through which light filters in. This mosque dates to the Lodhi era and was commissioned in the early 1500s. According to historical accounts, Sultan Sikandar Lodi granted a bag of moth lentils to his prime minister, Wazir Miya Bhoiya, who used its sale to fund the construction of the mosque. Over time the structure became known as Masjid Moth in reference to that origin. The building reflects characteristic Lodhi period work with robust stonework, pointed arches, and sequences of vaulted bays..
source_title: The interior corridor of Masjid Moth is built entirely of stone and lined with repeating arches through which light filters in. This mosque dates to the Lodhi era and was commissioned in the early 1500s. According to historical accounts, Sultan Sikandar Lodi granted a bag of moth lentils to his prime minister, Wazir Miya Bhoiya, who used its sale to fund the construction of the mosque. Over time the structure became known as Masjid Moth in reference to that origin. The building reflects characteristic Lodhi period work with robust stonework, pointed arches, and sequences of vaulted bays.
